<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-129-270  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 129 270.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Feb 5 1990 v9 n3 p6(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Justice Dept. will appeal ruling that it stole company's software.andO;(Justice Department to appeal federal court ruling that it stolecase management software from Inslaw Inc)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grimm, Vanessa Jo.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   INSLAW Inc. (cases).andO;Topic:     Legal ApplicationsLegal IssuesCourt CasesSoftware PiracyGovernment AgencyGovernment ContractsUnited States. Department of Justice.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Justice Dept.andP;  Will Appeal Ruling That It Stole Company's SoftwareandM;The Justice Department late last month announced it will appeal a federalcourt ruling that the department stole case management software from InslawInc.andM;The Department filed the notice with the U.S.andP;  District Court for theDistrict of Columbia.andP;  The notice marks the latest round in the four-yearbattle between Justice and the Washington software company.andM;Late last fall, senior District Court Judge William B. Bryant agreed with a1987 Bankruptcy Court ruling that Jutice officials stole from Inslaw advancedversions of the case management software, known as the Prosecutors ManagementInformation System or Promis.andP;  Justice officials continually have deniedwrongdoing.andM;Meanwhile, Inslaw has filed a motion with the Transportation Department Boardof contract Appeals asking that Justice be forced to pay about $2 million inback payments from the company's 1982 contract with the department.andM;The appeals board has jurisdiction over Justice contract disputes and heardthe original complaints made by Inslaw.andM;Inslaw and Justice also are awaiting an audit report on the contract from theDefense Contract Audit Agency.andM;Inslaw has asked the board to require Justice to assign the settling up ofthe contract to a contracting officer in another agency.andM;Justice awarded Inslaw a contract in 1982 to provide case management softwarefor U.S.andP;  attorneys' offices.andP;  But after halting much of the contract in1985, Justice stopped payments to Inslaw.andM;Inslaw president William A. Hamilton has charged that Justice tried to forcethe company into bankruptcy and get Promis into the public domain.andM;THe Inslaw motion said in similar cases the DOT board has ruled thatBankruptcy Court rulings are binding.andP;  The District Court ruling should beenough grounds for the board to order Justice to release the $2 million,Inslaw said.andM;Justice officials would not comment on Inslaw's DOT appeals board filingbecause the case still is being litigated.andO;</TEXT></DOC>